South Africa’s struggling state-owned power firm Eskom said on Tuesday that there was a high risk of power cuts this evening because of a sharp increase in unplanned outages. Eskom, which supplies more than 90% of the electricity in Africa’s most industrialised economy, has been grappling with labour unrest as it tries to reverse a decade of steep financial decline by cutting costs. “Customers are urged to switch off all non-essential appliances in an effort to reduce pressure on the power grid,” Eskom spokesman Khulu Phasiwe wrote on Twitter. Listen to the podcast with Phasiwe for more on the risks to Eskom’s power supply here.